CleanPlate
==========

Secure roommate chore coordination with an interactive client shell and a local
API server.

Requires Python 3.10+.
Third-party dependency: zxcvbn (`pip install zxcvbn`)

- Standard library only
- Python 3.10+
- macOS / Linux

Overview
--------

CleanPlate runs as a small client/server system:

- `python3 main.py serve` starts the API server
- `./cleanplate` opens the interactive client shell
- shell commands are parsed locally, then sent to the server
- the server owns the database and business logic

HTTPS is the default transport. The client validates the server's X.509
certificate and hostname, and the TLS stack requires TLS 1.3 when the local
Python/OpenSSL build supports it.

Persistent TLS Configuration
----------------------------

Startup is now streamlined through a shared config file: `cleanplate.ini`

The default file configures:

- client server URL
- client CA certificate path
- server host and port
- server certificate and key paths
- whether insecure HTTP is allowed

Default config:

```ini
[client]
server_url = https://127.0.0.1:8443
ca_cert = server.pem
allow_insecure_http = false

[server]
host = 127.0.0.1
port = 8443
tls_cert = server.pem
tls_key = server.key
allow_insecure_http = false
```

Because both client and server read this file, the normal secure startup flow is
just:

```bash
# Terminal 1
python3 main.py serve

# Terminal 2
./cleanplate
```

If you want a different config file, set `CLEANPLATE_CONFIG=/path/to/cleanplate.ini`.
Environment variables like `CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL`, `CLEANPLATE_CA_CERT`,
`CLEANPLATE_TLS_CERT`, and `CLEANPLATE_TLS_KEY` still override the file when needed.

CleanPlate also auto-loads a repo-local `.env` file if present, so env-based TLS
settings work without re-exporting them each time.

Quick Start
-----------

```bash
# Terminal 1
export CLEANPLATE_AUDIT_HMAC_KEY='replace-with-a-long-random-secret'
export CLEANPLATE_USERNAME_HMAC_KEY='replace-with-a-second-long-random-secret'
export CLEANPLATE_SESSION_HMAC_KEY='replace-with-a-third-long-random-secret'
python3 main.py serve

# Terminal 2
./cleanplate
```

Then work inside the shell:

```text
cleanplate> register alice
cleanplate> login alice
cleanplate> household create "42 Elm Street"
cleanplate> household list
cleanplate> exit
```

Interactive Shell
-----------------

Open the client shell with either:

- `./cleanplate`
- `python3 main.py interactive`

Inside the shell:

- `help` shows the command tree
- `exit`, `quit`, or `q` leaves the session
- omitted values are prompted for on more complex commands
- shorthand phrases are normalized into the structured command form

Examples:

```text
cleanplate> register alice
cleanplate> login alice
cleanplate> whoami
cleanplate> household create "Maple House"
cleanplate> household join aB3xQr_kLmN
cleanplate> chore create 1 "Take out trash"
cleanplate> chore reschedule 4 --due 2026-04-20
cleanplate> activity complete 4
cleanplate> activity incomplete 4
```

TLS / Certificate Validation
----------------------------

When the server starts from the default config, it presents the certificate in
`server.pem` and key in `server.key`. The client trusts the configured CA or
certificate bundle from `cleanplate.ini`.

You can also configure the same values in `.env`, for example:

```dotenv
CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL=https://127.0.0.1:8443
CLEANPLATE_CA_CERT=server.pem
CLEANPLATE_TLS_CERT=server.pem
CLEANPLATE_TLS_KEY=server.key
```

Best practice:

- use a hostname that matches the certificate SAN
- prefer a CA-issued certificate or a local development CA
- keep plaintext HTTP disabled except for temporary debugging

Important for local development:

- the certificate must include a `subjectAltName` entry for the host you connect to
- if you use `https://127.0.0.1:8443`, the cert needs `IP:127.0.0.1` in SAN
- if you use `https://localhost:8443`, the cert needs `DNS:localhost` in SAN
- a bare legacy `CN=127.0.0.1` without SAN is not enough for modern TLS hostname verification

If you absolutely need local plaintext HTTP, opt into it explicitly in both
places:

```ini
[client]
allow_insecure_http = true
server_url = http://127.0.0.1:8000

[server]
allow_insecure_http = true
port = 8000
```

Or override temporarily with environment variables / CLI flags:

```bash
python3 main.py serve --insecure-http --port 8000
export CLEANPLATE_ALLOW_INSECURE_HTTP=1
export CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8000
```

Sessions
--------

Local sessions are client-side files. By default they are terminal-scoped when
possible, so different terminals can stay logged in separately.

Optional overrides:

- `CLEANPLATE_SESSION_NAME`
- `CLEANPLATE_SESSION_PATH`

Command Reference
-----------------

Run all commands inside the `cleanplate>` prompt.

Common shorthand examples:

```text
register alice
login alice
reset-password alice
forgot-password alice
recover-password alice TOKEN_HERE
household create "Maple House"
household join aB3xQr_kLmN
household show "Maple House"
chore create "Maple House" "Take out trash"
chore assign 4 bob
chore list 1
chore show 4
chore reschedule 4 --due 2026-04-20
activity complete 4
activity incomplete 4
activity dispute 4 --reason "Still dirty"
activity audit 1
```

Identity & Access
-----------------

```text
register         [--username <name>]
login            [--username <name>]
reset-password   [--username <name>]
forgot-password  [--username <name>]
recover-password [--username <name>] [--token <reset_token>]
logout
whoami
```

Notes:

- `reset-password` is for a user who knows their current password
- `forgot-password` issues a one-time recovery token
- `recover-password` uses that token to set a new password

Household Management
--------------------

```text
household create        [--name "42 Elm St"]
household join          [--code <invite_token>]
household show          [--household <name>]
household list
household leave         [--household <name>]
household rename        [--household <name>] [--name <new_name>]
household rotate-invite [--household <name>]
household remove-member [--household <name>] [--username <name>]
household promote       [--household <name>] [--username <name>]
household demote        [--household <name>] [--username <name>]
household send-invite   [--household <name>] [--email <email_or_username>]
```

Notes:

- invite tokens are personal (tied to a specific user) and expire after 5 minutes
- admins use `send-invite` to email a token to a roommate by email address or username
- `promote` / `demote` can also be run as flat commands: `promote <username>`
- if the sole admin leaves, the longest-standing roommate is automatically promoted
- if the last member leaves, the household is deleted

Chore Management
----------------

```text
chore create     [--household <id>] [--title "Take out trash"] [--description "..."] [--due YYYY-MM-DD] [--assign <name>]...
chore assign     [--chore <id>] [--username <name>]
chore list       [--household <id>] [--status pending|complete|disputed] [--mine] [--overdue]
chore show       [--chore <id>]
chore reschedule [--chore <id>] [--due YYYY-MM-DD]
```

Notes:

- chore titles are not treated as globally unique; recurring chores can reuse a name
- chores can have multiple assignees
- `chore reschedule` can both add a first due date and change an existing one

---
Activity & Completion

  activity complete   [--chore <id>]
  activity incomplete [--chore <id>]
  activity dispute    [--chore <id>] [--reason "..."]
  activity resolve    [--complaint <id>] [--outcome uphold|dismiss] [--note "..."]
  activity audit      [--household <id>]
  activity poll

---
Notes:

- any assigned roommate can mark a shared chore complete
- assigned roommates and admins can also mark a completed chore back to `pending`
- disputes remain available for "redo" and complaint resolution workflows

---
EXAMPLE WALKTHROUGH
---
  # Terminal 1
  python3 main.py serve

  ---
  ./cleanplate
  ---
  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> register bob

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> household create "42 Elm Street"
  cleanplate> household send-invite "42 Elm Street" bob   (emails bob a personal token)

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> household join <token_from_email>

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> chore create "42 Elm Street" "Vacuum living room" --due 2026-04-10 --assign bob --assign alice

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> activity complete 1

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> activity incomplete 1
  cleanplate> chore reschedule 1 --due 2026-04-17
  cleanplate> activity audit 1
  cleanplate> exit

FILE LAYOUT
---

  cleanplate        Shell wrapper that launches the interactive client
  main.py           Entry point for the server and interactive shell
  client_cli.py     Client-side shell handlers and parser wiring
  api_client.py     JSON/HTTP client helper
  api_server.py     HTTP transport and server-side command dispatch
  db.py             SQLite schema and query helpers
  session.py        Local client session storage and request-scoped session override
  auth.py           Registration, login, password reset/recovery
  households.py     Household creation, joining, invites, membership
  chores.py         Chore creation, assignment, listing, rescheduling
  activity.py       Completion, incompletion, disputes, audit log, notifications
  cleanplate.db     Created automatically on first run


ARCHITECTURE
---

Client shell:

- ./cleanplate or python3 main.py interactive
- parses commands locally
- prompts for missing inputs
- sends requests to the API server
- stores the local session file

Server:

- python3 main.py serve
- receives JSON requests over HTTP
- dispatches them to the feature modules
- owns all database access

Feature modules:

- auth.py, households.py, chores.py, and activity.py
- contain the actual business logic, validation, role checks, and audit writes

Database:

- SQLite via `db.py`
- accessed only on the server side

---
SECURITY NOTES
---

Passwords:

- stored with `scrypt`
- must pass zxcvbn score ≥ 2 and not appear in common/breached password lists

Usernames:

- stored as HMAC-SHA256 digests at rest
- human-readable usernames are kept separately as `display_name`
- server key must come from `CLEANPLATE_USERNAME_HMAC_KEY`
- `USERNAME_HMAC_KEY` is also accepted for compatibility

Password recovery:

- recovery uses one-time reset tokens stored as hashes
- tokens expire after 5 minutes
- prototype mode currently prints the token instead of sending email

Audit log:

- HMAC-SHA256 chained
- `verify_chain()` detects tampering
- server key must come from `CLEANPLATE_AUDIT_HMAC_KEY`
- `AUDIT_HMAC_KEY` is also accepted for compatibility

Sessions:

- stored locally on the client side
- expire automatically after the configured TTL in `session.py`
- server trusts only signed session tokens, not client-supplied identity fields
- signing key must come from `CLEANPLATE_SESSION_HMAC_KEY`
- `SESSION_HMAC_KEY` is also accepted for compatibility
- cleared on logout

Authorization:

- role checks happen inside the command handlers, not just at login

Multi-household support:

- a single user can belong to multiple households
- membership is tracked per `(user_id, household_id)`
